docs.name: Combine.Char

values.name: anyChar
values.comment:
Parse any character.

    parse anyChar "a" ==
      (Ok 'a', { input = "", position = 1 })

    parse anyChar "" ==
      (Err ["expected any character"], { input = "", position = 0 })

values.name: char
values.comment:
Parse an exact character match.

    parse (char 'a') "a" ==
      (Ok 'a', { input = "", position = 1 })

    parse (char 'a') "b" ==
      (Err ["expected 'a'"], { input = "b", position = 0 })

values.name: crlf
values.comment: Parse a `\r\n` sequence, returning a `\n` character.

values.name: digit
values.comment: Parse any base 10 digit.

values.name: eol
values.comment: Parse an end of line character or sequence, returning a `\n` character.

values.comment: Parse any base 16 digit.

values.comment: Parse any lowercase character.

values.name: newline
values.comment: Parse a `\n` character.

values.name: noneOf
values.comment:
Parse a character that is not in the given list.

    parse (noneOf ['a', 'b']) "c" ==
      (Ok 'c', { input = "", position = 1 })

    parse (noneOf ['a', 'b']) "a" ==
      (Err ["expected none of ['a','b']"], { input = "a", position = 0 })

values.name: octDigit
values.comment: Parse any base 8 digit.

values.name: oneOf
values.comment:
Parse a character from the given list.

    parse (oneOf ['a', 'b']) "a" ==
      (Ok 'a', { input = "", position = 1 })

    parse (oneOf ['a', 'b']) "c" ==
      (Err ["expected one of ['a','b']"], { input = "c", position = 0 })

values.name: satisfy
values.comment:
Parse a character matching the predicate.

    parse (satisfy ((==) 'a')) "a" ==
      (Ok 'a', { input = "", position = 1 })

    parse (satisfy ((==) 'a')) "b" ==
      (Err ["could not satisfy predicate"], { input = "b", position = 0 })

docs.name: Combine.Infix

values.comment:
Join two parsers, ignoring the result of the one on the left.

    unprefix : Parser String
    unprefix = string ">" *> while ((==) ' ') *> while ((/=) ' ')

    parse unprefix "> a" == (Ok "a", { input = "", position = 3 })
values.type: Combine.Parser x -> Combine.Parser res -> Combine.Parser res

values.comment: Variant of `Combine.map` that ignores the Parser's result.
Synonym for `Combine.map`.

Join two parsers, ignoring the result of the one on the right.

    unsuffix : Parser String
    unsuffix = regex "[a-z]" <* regex "[!?]"

    parse unsuffix "a!" == (Ok "a", { input = "", position = 2 })
values.type: Combine.Parser res -> Combine.Parser x -> Combine.Parser res

values.comment: Synonym for `Combine.andMap`.
values.type: Combine.Parser (res -> res') -> Combine.Parser res -> Combine.Parser res'

values.comment:
Variant of `Combine.mapError` that replaces the Parser's error
with a List of a single string.

    parse (string "a" <?> "gimme an 'a'") "b" ==
      (Err ["gimme an 'a'"], { input = "b", position = 0 })
Synonym for `or`.
values.type: Combine.Parser res -> Combine.Parser res -> Combine.Parser res

docs.name: Combine

aliases.name: Context
aliases.comment: The contex over which `Parser`s operate.

types.name: Parser
types.comment:
The Parser type.

At their core, `Parser`s simply wrap functions from a `Context` to a
tuple of a `Result res` and a new `Context`.

values.name: andMap
values.comment:
Sequence two parsers.

    import Maybe
    import Result
    import String

    num : Parser Int
    num = (Maybe.withDefault 0 << Result.toMaybe << String.toInt) `map` regex "[0-9]+"

    sum : Parser Int
    sum = (+) `map` (num <* string "+") `andMap` num

    parse sum "1+2" ==
      (Ok 3, { input = "", position = 3 })
values.type: Combine.Parser (a -> res) -> Combine.Parser a -> Combine.Parser res

values.name: andThen
values.comment:
Sequence two parsers, passing the result of the first parser to a
function that returns the second parser. The value of the second
parser is returned on success.

    import Combine.Num exposing (int)

    choosy : Parser String
    choosy =
      int
        `andThen` \x -> if x % 2 == 0
                        then string " is even"
                        else string " is odd"

    parse choosy "1 is odd" ==
      (Ok " is odd", { input = "", position = 8 })

    parse choosy "1 is even" ==
      (Err ["expected \" is odd\""], { input = " is even", position = 1 })
values.type: Combine.Parser res -> (res -> Combine.Parser res') -> Combine.Parser res'

values.name: app
values.comment: Unwrap a parser so it can be applied to a context.
values.type: Combine.Parser res -> Combine.Context -> ( Combine.Result res, Combine.Context )

values.name: between
values.comment:
Parse something between two other parsers.

The parser

    between (string "(") (string ")") (string "a")

is equivalent to the parser

    string "(" *> string "a" <* string ")"
values.type: Combine.Parser left -> Combine.Parser right -> Combine.Parser res -> Combine.Parser res

values.name: bimap
values.comment: Transform both the result and error message of a parser.
values.type: (res -> res') -> (List String -> List String) -> Combine.Parser res -> Combine.Parser res'

values.name: braces
values.comment: Parse something between braces `{}`.

values.name: brackets
values.comment: Parse something between square brackets `[]`.

values.name: chainl
values.comment:
Parse one or more occurences of `p` separated by `op`, recursively
apply all functions returned by `op` to the values returned by `p`. See
the `examples/Calc.elm` file for an example.
values.type: Combine.Parser res -> Combine.Parser (res -> res -> res) -> Combine.Parser res

values.name: chainr
values.comment:
Similar to `chainl` but functions of `op` are applied in
right-associative order to the values of `p`.
values.type: Combine.Parser res -> Combine.Parser (res -> res -> res) -> Combine.Parser res

values.name: choice
values.comment:
Choose between a list of parsers.

    parse (choice [string "a", string "b"]) "a" ==
      (Ok "a", { input = "", position = 1 })

    parse (choice [string "a", string "b"]) "b" ==
      (Ok "b", { input = "", position = 1 })

values.name: count
values.comment: Parse `n` occurences of `p`.

values.name: end
values.comment:
Fail when the input is not empty.

    parse end "" == (Ok (), { input = "", position = 0 })
    parse end "a" == (Err ["expected end of input"], { input = "a", position = 0 })

values.name: fail
values.comment: Fail without consuming any input.

values.name: many
values.comment:
Apply a parser until it fails and return a list of the results.

    parse (many (string "a")) "aaab" ==
      (Ok ["a", "a", "a"], { input = "b", position = 3 })

    parse (many (string "a")) "" ==
      (Ok [], { input = "", position = 0 })

values.name: many1
values.comment:
Parse at least one result.

    parse (many1 (string "a")) "a" ==
      (Ok ["a"], { input = "", position = 1 })

    parse (many1 (string "a")) "" ==
      (Err ["expected \"a\""], { input = "", position = 0 })

values.name: manyTill
values.comment:
Apply parser `p` zero or more times until parser `end`
succeeds. On success, the list of `p`'s results is returned.

    string "<!--" *> manyTill anyChar (string "-->")
values.type: Combine.Parser res -> Combine.Parser end -> Combine.Parser (List res)

values.name: map
values.comment:
Transform the result of a parser.

    parse (map String.toUpper (string "a")) "a" ==
      (Ok "A", { input = "", position = 1 })

values.name: mapError
values.comment:
Transform the error of a parser.

    parse (mapError (\_ -> ["bad input"]) (string "a")) "b" ==
      (Err ["bad input"], { input = "b", position = 0 })
values.type: (List String -> List String) -> Combine.Parser res -> Combine.Parser res

values.name: maybe
values.comment:
Wrap the return value into a `Maybe`. Returns `Nothing` on failure.

    parse (maybe (string "a")) "a" ==
      (Ok (Just "a"), { input = "", position = 1 })

    parse (maybe (string "a")) "b" ==
      (Ok Nothing, { input = "b", position = 0 })

values.name: optional
values.comment:
Return a default value when the given parser fails.

    letterA : Parser String
    letterA = optional "a" (string "a")

    parse letterA "a" == (Ok "a", { input = "", position = 1 })
    parse letterA "b" == (Ok "a", { input = "b", position = 0 })

values.name: or
values.comment:
Choose between two parsers.

    parse (string "a" `or` string "b") "a" ==
      (Ok "a", { input = "", position = 1 })

    parse (string "a" `or` string "b") "b" ==
      (Ok "b", { input = "", position = 1 })

    parse (string "a" `or` string "b") "c" ==
      (Err ["expected \"a\"", "expected \"b\""], { input = "c", position = 0 })
values.type: Combine.Parser res -> Combine.Parser res -> Combine.Parser res

values.name: parens
values.comment: Parse something between parentheses.

values.name: parse
values.comment:
Parse a string.

    import Combine.Num exposing (int)

    parse int "123" ==
      (Ok 123, { input = "", position = 3 })

    parse int "abc" ==
      (Err ["expected an integer"], { input = "abc", position = 0 })
values.type: Combine.Parser res -> String -> ( Combine.Result res, Combine.Context )

values.name: primitive
values.comment:
Construct a new primitive Parser.

If you find yourself reaching for this function often consider opening
a [Github issue](https://github.com/Bogdanp/elm-combine/issues) with
the library to have your custom Parsers included in the standard
distribution.

values.name: rec
values.comment:
Defer a parser's evaluation.

    type E = ETerm String | EList (List E)

    whitespace : Parser String
    whitespace = regex "[ \t\r\n]*"

    term : Parser E
    term = ETerm `map` (whitespace *> regex "[a-zA-Z]+" <* whitespace)

    list : Parser E
    list = rec (\() -> EList `map` (string "(" *> many (term `or` list) <* string ")"))

    parse list "" ==
      (Err ["expected \"(\""], { input = "", position = 0 })

    parse list "()" ==
      (Ok (EList []), { input = "", position = 2 })

    parse list "(a (b c))" ==
      (Ok (EList [ETerm "a", EList [ETerm "b", ETerm "c"]]), { input = "", position = 9 })

values.name: regex
values.comment:
Parse a Regex match.

Regular expressions must match from the beginning of the input and their
subgroups are ignored. A `^` is added implicitly to the beginning of
every pattern unless one already exists.

    parse (regex "a+") "aaaaab" ==
      (Ok "aaaaa", { input = "b", position = 5 })

values.name: sepBy
values.comment:
Parser zero or more occurences of one parser separated by another.

    parse (sepBy (string ",") (string "a")) "b" ==
      (Ok [], { input = "b", position = 0 })

    parse (sepBy (string ",") (string "a")) "a,a,a" ==
      (Ok ["a", "a", "a"], { input = "", position = 5 })

    parse (sepBy (string ",") (string "a")) "a,a,b" ==
      (Ok ["a", "a"], { input = ",b", position = 3 })
values.type: Combine.Parser x -> Combine.Parser res -> Combine.Parser (List res)

values.name: sepBy1
values.comment: Parse one or more occurences of one parser separated by another.
values.type: Combine.Parser x -> Combine.Parser res -> Combine.Parser (List res)

values.name: sepEndBy
values.comment:
Parse zero or more occurences of one parser separated and
optionally ended by another.

    parse (sepEndBy (string ",") (string "a")) "a,a,a," ==
      (Ok ["a", "a", "a"], { input = "", position = 6 })
values.type: Combine.Parser x -> Combine.Parser res -> Combine.Parser (List res)

values.name: sepEndBy1
values.comment:
Parse one or more occurences of one parser separated and
optionally ended by another.

    parse (sepEndBy1 (string ",") (string "a")) "" ==
      (Err ["expected \"a\""], { input = "", position = 0 })

    parse (sepEndBy1 (string ",") (string "a")) "a" ==
      (Ok ["a"], { input = "", position = 1 })

    parse (sepEndBy1 (string ",") (string "a")) "a," ==
      (Ok ["a"], { input = "", position = 2 })
values.type: Combine.Parser x -> Combine.Parser res -> Combine.Parser (List res)

values.name: sequence
values.comment:
Run a list of parsers in sequence, accumulating the results.

    parse (sequence [string "a", string "b"]) "ab" ==
      (Ok ["a", "b"], { input = "", position = 2 })

    parse (sequence [string "a", string "b"]) "ac" ==
      (Err ["expected \"b\"", { input = "c", position = 1 })

values.name: skip
values.comment: Apply a parser and skip its result.

values.name: skipMany
values.comment: Apply a parser and skip its result many times.

values.name: skipMany1
values.comment: Apply a parser and skip its result at least once.

values.name: string
values.comment:
Parse an exact string match.

    parse (string "hello") "hello world" ==
      (Ok "hello", { input = " world", position = 5 })

    parse (string "hello") "goodbye" ==
      (Err ["expected \"hello\""], { input = "goodbye", position = 0 })

values.name: succeed
values.comment:
Return a value without consuming any input.

    parse (succeed 1) "a" ==
      (Ok 1, { input = "a", position = 0 })

values.name: while
values.comment:
Consume input while the predicate matches.

    parse (while ((/=) ' ')) "test 123" ==
      (Ok "test", { input = " 123", position = 4 })

aliases.type: { placeholder : String , classNamespace : String , inputClassList : List ( String, Bool ) , inputName : Maybe.Maybe String , isDisabled : Date.Date -> Bool , dateFormatter : Date.Date -> String , dayFormatter : Date.Day -> String , monthFormatter : Date.Month -> String , yearFormatter : Int -> String , firstDayOfWeek : Date.Day , pickedDate : Maybe.Maybe Date.Date }

values.name: defaultSettings
init
values.comment:
Initialize a DatePicker given a Settings record.  You must execute
the returned command for the date picker to behave correctly.


    init =
      let
         (datePicker, datePickerFx) =
           DatePicker.init defaultSettings
      in
         { picker = datePicker } ! [ Cmd.map ToDatePicker datePickerfx ]

values.name: update
values.comment:
The date picker update function.  The third value in the returned
tuple represents the picked date, it is `Nothing` if no date was
picked or if the previously-picked date has not changed and `Just`
some date if it has.
values.type: DatePicker.Msg -> DatePicker.DatePicker -> ( DatePicker.DatePicker , Platform.Cmd.Cmd DatePicker.Msg , Maybe.Maybe Date.Date )

docs.name: Route

types.name: Route
types.comment:
Routes represent concrete parsers for paths. Routes can be combined
and they keep track of their path components in order to provide
automatic reverse routing.

types.name: Router
types.comment:
A Router is, at its core, a List of Routes.

    sitemap = router [routeA, routeB]

values.comment:
A synonym for `route`.

    type Sitemap
      = HomeR ()

    homeR : Route Sitemap
    homeR = HomeR := static ""

A synonym for `prefix`.

    type Sitemap
      = UserR Int

    userR = UserR := "users" <//> int
    sitemap = router [userR]

    > match sitemap "/users/"
    Nothing : Maybe.Maybe Sitemap

    > match sitemap "/users/1"
    Just (UserR 1) : Maybe.Maybe Sitemap

A synonym for `and`.

    type Sitemap
      = AddR (Int, Int)

    addR = AddR := int </> int
    sitemap = router [addR]

    > match sitemap "/1/2"
    Just (AddR (1,2)) : Maybe.Maybe Sitemap
values.type: Route.Route a -> Route.Route b -> Route.Route ( a, b )

values.comment:
A synonym for `suffix`.

    type Sitemap
      = UserEmailsR Int
      = UserEmailsR' (Int, ())

    userEmailsR = UserEmailsR := "users" <//> int <> "emails"
    userEmailsR' = UserEmailsR' := "users" <//> int </> static "emails"
    sitemap = router [userEmailsR, userEmailsR']

    > match sitemap "/users/1/emails"
    Just (UserEmailsR 1) : Maybe.Maybe Sitemap

    > match sitemap "/users/1/emails-static"
    Just (UserEmailsR' (1,())) : Maybe.Maybe Sitemap

values.name: and
values.comment:
Compose two Routes.

    type Sitemap
      = AddR (Int, Int)

    addR = AddR := int `and` int
    sitemap = router [addR]

    > match sitemap "/1/2"
    Just (AddR (1,2)) : Maybe.Maybe Sitemap
values.type: Route.Route a -> Route.Route b -> Route.Route ( a, b )

values.name: child
values.comment:
Routers may be nested. This function is useful in situations
where you want to split your routes into multiple types while still
maintaining a single top-level "site map".

    type AdminSitemap
      = AdminHomeR ()
      | AdminUsersR ()

    adminHomeR = AdminHomeR := static "admin"
    adminUsersR = AdminHomeR := "admin" <//> static "users"
    adminSitemap = router [adminHomeR, adminUsersR]

    type Sitemap
      = HomeR ()
      | BlogR ()
      | AdminR AdminSitemap

    homeR = HomeR := static ""
    blogR = BlogR := static "blog"
    sitemap = router [homeR, blogR, child AdminR adminSitemap]

See `examples/Reuse.elm` for a more advanced use case of this.

values.name: custom
values.comment:
Create a Route with a custom Parser.

    import Combine exposing (..)
    import Combine.Infix exposing (..)

    type Category
      = Snippet
      | Post

    type Sitemap
      = CategoryR Category

    categoryR = CategoryR := "categories" <//> custom categoryParser
    sitemap = router [categoryR]

    > match sitemap "/categories/a"
    Nothing : Maybe.Maybe Sitemap

    > match sitemap "/categories/Post"
    Just (CategoryR Post) : Maybe.Maybe Sitemap

    > match sitemap "/categories/Snippet"
    Just (CategoryR Snippet) : Maybe.Maybe Sitemap

See `examples/Custom.elm` for a complete example.

values.name: int
values.comment:
A Route that matches any integer.

    type Sitemap
      = UserR Int

    userR = UserR := "users" <//> int
    sitemap = router [userR]

    > match sitemap "/users/a"
    Nothing : Maybe.Maybe Sitemap

    > match sitemap "/users/1"
    Just (UserR 1) : Maybe.Maybe Sitemap

    > match sitemap "/users/-1"
    Just (UserR -1) : Maybe.Maybe Sitemap

values.name: match
values.comment:
Given a Router and an arbitrary String representing a path, this
function will return the first Route that matches that path.

    type Sitemap
      = HomeR ()
      | UsersR ()
      | UserR Int

    homeR = HomeR := static ""
    usersR = UsersR := static "users"
    usersR = UserR := "users" <//> int
    sitemap = router [homeR, userR, usersR]

    > match siteMap "/a"
    Nothing : Maybe.Maybe Sitemap

    > match siteMap "/"
    Just (HomeR ()) : Maybe.Maybe Sitemap

    > match siteMap "/users"
    Just (UsersR ()) : Maybe.Maybe Sitemap

    > match siteMap "/users/1"
    Just (UserR 1) : Maybe.Maybe Sitemap

    > match siteMap "/users/1"
    Just (UserR 1) : Maybe.Maybe Sitemap

values.name: prefix
values.comment:
Prefix a `Route` with a string.

    type Sitemap
      = UserR Int

    userR = UserR := prefix "users" int
    sitemap = router [userR]

    > match sitemap "/users/"
    Nothing : Maybe.Maybe Sitemap

    > match sitemap "/users/1"
    Just (UserR 1) : Maybe.Maybe Sitemap

values.name: reverse
values.comment:
Render a path given a route and a list of route components.

    type Sitemap
      = HomeR ()
      | UsersR ()
      | UserR Int

    homeR = HomeR := static ""
    usersR = UsersR := static "users"
    usersR = UserR := "users" <//> int
    sitemap = router [homeR, userR, usersR]

    > reverse homeR []
    "/"

    > reverse usersR []
    "/users"

    > reverse userR ["1"]
    "/users/1"

If you are willing to write some boilerplate, this function can be used
to construct a reasonably-safe reverse routing function specific to your
application:

    render : Sitemap -> String
    render r =
      case r of
        HomeR () -> reverse homeR []
        UsersR () -> reverse usersR []
        UserR uid -> reverse userR [toString uid]

    > render (HomeR ())
    "/"

    > render (UsersR ())
    "/users"

    > render (UserR 1)
    "/users/1"

This function will crash at runtime if there is a mismatch between the
route and the list of arguments that is passed in. For example:

    > reverse deepR []
    Error: Ran into a `Debug.crash` in module `Route`

    This was caused by the `case` expression between lines 145 and 175.
    One of the branches ended with a crash and the following value got through:

        ([],[CInt,CInt,CInt])

    The message provided by the code author is:

        'reverse' called with an unexpected number of arguments

    > reverse deepR ["a"]
    Error: Ran into a `Debug.crash` in module `Route`

    This was caused by the `case` expression between lines 171 and 176.
    One of the branches ended with a crash and the following value got through:

        Err ("could not convert string 'a' to an Int")

    The message provided by the code author is:

        could not convert string 'a' to an Int in a call to 'reverse'

values.name: route
values.comment:
Declare a Route.

    type Sitemap
      = HomeR ()

    homeR : Route Sitemap
    homeR = route HomeR (static "")

values.name: router
values.comment:
Construct a Router from a list of Routes.

    type Sitemap
      = HomeR ()
      | BlogR ()

    homeR = HomeR := static ""
    blogR = BlogR := static "blog"
    sitemap = router [homeR, blogR]

values.name: static
values.comment:
Create a Route that matches a static String.

    type Sitemap
      = BlogR ()

    blogR = BlogR := static "blog"
    sitemap = router [blogR]

    > match sitemap "/blog"
    Just (BlogR ()) : Maybe.Maybe Sitemap

values.name: string
values.comment:
A Route that matches any string.

    type Sitemap
      = PostR String

    postR = PostR := "posts" <//> string
    sitemap = router [postR]

    > match sitemap "/posts/"
    Nothing : Maybe.Maybe Sitemap

    > match sitemap "/posts/hello-world/test"
    Nothing : Maybe.Maybe Sitemap

    > match sitemap "/posts/hello-world"
    Just (PostR "hello-world") : Maybe.Maybe Sitemap

values.name: suffix
values.comment:
Suffix a `Route` with a string. This can be used in place
of `static` when there are static path components at the end of a
path.

    type Sitemap
      = UserEmailsR Int
      = UserEmailsR' (Int, ())

    userEmailsR = UserEmailsR := suffix "emails" (prefix "users" int)
    userEmailsR' = UserEmailsR' := prefix "users" int `and` static "emails-static"
    sitemap = router [userEmailsR, userEmailsR']

    > match sitemap "/users/1/emails"
    Just (UserEmailsR 1) : Maybe.Maybe Sitemap

    > match sitemap "/users/1/emails-static"
    Just (UserEmailsR' (1,())) : Maybe.Maybe Sitemap

docs.name: Route.QueryString
docs.comment:
This module exposes functions for working with query strings.

You can manipulate query strings:

    empty
      |> add "a" "hello"
      |> add "a" "goodbye"
      |> add "b" "1"
      |> render

And you can parse and extract their parameters:

    let
      qs = parse "?a=1&a=2&a=test&b=hello"
      a = many int qs
      b = one string qs |> Maybe.withDefault "goodbye"
    in
      (a, b)

## Types
@docs QueryString

## Constructing QueryStrings
@docs parse, empty

## Manipulating parameters
@docs render, add, remove, filter

## Extracting parameters
@docs all, one, many

### Parsers
@docs string, int

types.name: QueryString
types.comment: Represents a parsed query string.

values.name: add
values.comment:
Add a value to a key.

    > parse "?a=1&b=a&a=c" |> add "a" "2" |> render
    "?a=2&a=1&a=c&b=a" : String

    > parse "?a=1&b=a&a=c" |> add "d" "hello" |> render
    "?a=1&a=c&b=a&d=hello" : String

values.name: all
values.comment:
Retrieve all of the values for a given key.

    > parse "?a=1&a=2" |> all "a"
    ["1","2"] : List String

    > parse "?a=1&a=2" |> all "b"
    [] : List String

values.name: empty
values.comment: Construct an empty QueryString.

values.name: filter
values.comment:
Filter a key's values.

    > parse "?a=1&b=a&a=c" |> filter "a" ((==) "1") |> render
    "?a=1&b=a" : String

values.name: int
values.comment: A Parser that accepts any integer.

values.name: many
values.comment:
Retrieve zero or more values for some key. Values are funneled
through the given parser before being returned.

    > parse "?a=1&a=c&a=2" |> many int "a"
    [1,2] : List Int
values.type: Combine.Parser a -> String -> Route.QueryString.QueryString -> List a

values.name: one
values.comment:
Retrieve a single value for a given key. Values are funneled through
the given parser before being returned.

    > parse "?a=1&a=2" |> one string "a"
    Just "2" : Maybe.Maybe String

    > parse "?a=1&a=2" |> one int "a"
    Just 2 : Maybe.Maybe Int

    > parse "?a=1&a=c" |> one int "a"
    Just 1 : Maybe.Maybe Int
values.type: Combine.Parser a -> String -> Route.QueryString.QueryString -> Maybe.Maybe a

values.name: parse
values.comment:
Turn a String into a QueryString. The initial `?` is optional.

    > parse ""
    QueryString (Dict.fromList []) : Route.QueryString.QueryString

    > parse "?a=1&b=c&a=2"
    QueryString (Dict.fromList [("a",["1","2"]),("b",["c"])])
        : Route.QueryString.QueryString

    > parse "a=1&b=c&a=2"
    QueryString (Dict.fromList [("a",["1","2"]),("b",["c"])])
        : Route.QueryString.QueryString

values.name: remove
values.comment:
Remove a key.

    > parse "?a=1&b=a&a=c" |> remove "a" |> render
    "?b=a" : String

    > parse "?a=1&b=a&a=c" |> remove "c" |> render
    "?a=1&a=c&b=a" : String

values.name: render
values.comment:
Render a QueryString to a String.

    > parse "?a=1&b=a&a=c" |> render
    "?a=1&a=c&b=a" : String

values.name: string
values.comment: A Parser that accepts any string.

docs.name: Parser.Char
docs.comment:
Parsing characters

@docs upper, lower, between, parenthesized, bracketed, braced, quoted, singleQuoted

values.name: between
values.comment: Parse a parser between two `Chars`
values.type: Char -> Char -> Parser.Parser result -> Parser.Parser result

values.name: braced
values.comment: Parses a parser between braces `{` and `}`

values.name: bracketed
values.comment: Parses a parser between brackets `[` and `]`

values.name: lower
values.comment: Parse a lower case character

values.name: parenthesized
values.comment: Parse a parser between parentheses `(` and `)`

values.name: quoted
values.comment: Parses a parser between quotes `"` and `"`

values.name: singleQuoted
values.comment: Parses a parser between quotes `'` and `'`

values.name: upper
values.comment: Parse a upper case character

docs.name: Parser.Number
docs.comment:
Parsing numbers

@docs digit, natural, integer, float, sign

values.name: digit
values.comment: Parse a digit

values.name: float
values.comment: Parse a float with optional sign

values.name: integer
values.comment: Parse an integer with optional sign

values.name: natural
values.comment: Parse a natural number

values.name: sign
values.comment: Parse a optional sign, succeeds with a -1 if it matches a minus `Char`, otherwise it returns 1

docs.name: Parser

types.name: Parser
types.comment: Parser type

values.comment: Variant of `and` that ignores the result of the parser at the left
values.type: Parser.Parser x -> Parser.Parser result -> Parser.Parser result

values.comment: Variant of `map` that ignores the result of the parser
Variant of `and` that ignores the result of the parser at the right
values.type: Parser.Parser result -> Parser.Parser x -> Parser.Parser result

values.name: and
values.comment:
Sequence two parsers (infix version)

    type Date = Date Int Int Int
    date = Date `map` year `and` month `and` day
values.type: Parser.Parser (result -> result2) -> Parser.Parser result -> Parser.Parser result2

values.name: andMap
values.comment:
Sequence two parsers

    type Date = Date Int Int Int
    date =
        map Date year
        |> andMap month
        |> andMap day
values.type: Parser.Parser result -> Parser.Parser (result -> result2) -> Parser.Parser result2

values.name: andThen
values.comment:
Sequence two parsers, but pass the result of the first parser to the second parser.
    This is useful for creating context sensitive parsers like XML.

    tag = openTag
        |> andThen (tagLiteral)
values.type: Parser.Parser result -> (result -> Parser.Parser result2) -> Parser.Parser result2

values.name: choice
values.comment: Combine a list of parsers

values.name: empty
values.comment: Parser that always fails

values.name: end
values.comment: Succeeds when input is empty

values.name: many
values.comment: Parses zero or more occurences of a parser

values.name: map
values.comment:
Map a function over the result of the parser
      -- Counts the amount of digits
      count : Parser Int
      count = map length (many digit)

values.name: optional
values.comment: Parses an optional element

values.name: or
values.comment:
Choice between two parsers

      oneOrTwo = symbol '1' `or` symbol '2'
values.type: Parser.Parser result -> Parser.Parser result -> Parser.Parser result

values.name: parse
values.comment: Parse a `String` using a parser, return first result
values.type: Parser.Parser result -> String -> Result.Result String result

values.name: parseAll
values.comment: Parse a `String` using a parser, return list of results
values.type: Parser.Parser result -> String -> Result.Result String (List result)

values.name: recursively
values.comment:
For realizing otherwise inexpressible recursive grammars. For
example, while

    bbbba = (symbol 'a') `or` (symbol 'b' *> bbbba)

will fail at runtime with a non-termination issue, the replacement

    bbbba = (symbol 'a') `or` (symbol 'b' *> recursively (\() -> bbbba))

is safe.

values.name: satisfy
values.comment: Parser that satisfies a given predicate

values.name: separatedBy
values.comment:
Parses a sequence of the first parser, separated by the second parser
```
naturals = separatedBy Number.natural (symbol ',')
```
values.type: Parser.Parser result -> Parser.Parser result2 -> Parser.Parser (List result)

values.name: some
values.comment: Parses one or more occurences of a parser

values.name: succeed
values.comment: Parser that always succeeds without consuming input

values.name: symbol
values.comment: Parses a symbol

values.name: token
values.comment: Parses a token of symbols

values.comment:
```elm
(\x y -> bar <| foo x y)
```


```elm

foo >>> bar
```

```elm
(\x y z -> foo x y z |> bar)
```

docs.name: Return

aliases.name: ReturnF
aliases.type: Return.Return msg model -> Return.Return msg model

values.comment:
Go point free with `andThen` chaining. Looking at the example from `andThen`

```elm
resulting : Return msg { model | bar : Int }
resulting =
  myReturn `andThen` foo
           `andThen` foo
           `andThen` foo
```

this code roughly becomes:

```elm
doFoo3Times : { model | bar : Int } -> Return msg { model | bar : Int }
doFoo3Times =
  foo >>> foo >>> foo
```
values.type: (b -> Return.Return msg c) -> (a -> Return.Return msg b) -> a -> Return.Return msg c
(a -> Return.Return msg b) -> (b -> Return.Return msg c) -> a -> Return.Return msg c

values.name: andMap
values.comment: Map an `Return` into a `Return` containing a `Model` function
values.type: Return.Return msg (a -> b) -> Return.Return msg a -> Return.Return msg b

values.name: andThen
values.comment:
Chain together expressions from `Model` to `Return`.

```elm
-- arbitrary function to demonstrate
foo : Model -> Return Msg Model
foo ({bar} as model) =
  -- forking logic
  if bar < 10
  -- that side effects may be added
  then (model, getAjaxThing)
  -- that the model may be updated
  else ({model | bar = model.bar - 2 }, Cmd.none)
```

They are now chainable with `andThen`...

```elm
resulting : Return msg { model | bar : Int }
resulting =
  myReturn `andThen` foo
           `andThen` foo
           `andThen` foo
```

Here we changed up `foo` three times, but we can use any function of
type `(a -> Return msg b)`.

Commands will be accumulated automatically as is the case with all
functions in this library.
values.type: Return.Return msg a -> (a -> Return.Return msg b) -> Return.Return msg b

Map over both the model and the msg type of the `Return`.
This is useful for easily embedding a `Return` in a Union Type.
For example

```elm

type Model = FooModel Foo.Model

...

update : Msg -> Model -> Return Msg Model

   case msg of

      |> mapBoth Foo FooModel
```

docs.name: Router

aliases.name: Route
aliases.comment: A Route is a function from a string to some value or computation.

aliases.name: Router
aliases.comment: A Router is a tuple containing a string and its associated route

values.comment:
Operator to offer easy-to-read DSL for matching routes. This is an alias
for the `(,)` tuple constructor function.

values.name: match
values.comment:
`match` allows you to select an appropriate route depending on the
given input string. `match` takes a list of routers and a default route,
which acts as a catch-all and returns a route. Returning a route allows
for nested routes.

Example:

    mainRoute : Route Html
    mainRoute = match
      [ "/"           :-> displayHomePage
      , "/index.html" :-> displayHomePage
      , "/blog"       :-> blogRoute
      , "/contact"    :-> displayContactsPage
      ] display404Page

    blogRoute : Route Html
    blogRoute = match
      [ "/"             :-> displayBlogPostListing
      , "/entry1.html"  :-> displayEntry1
      , "/entry2.html"  :-> displayEntry2
      ] display404Page


In some cases, it important to understand how `match` works. Suppose you have
the input path "/users/4873/profile.html" and there is a router that matches
"/users" with an associated route `usersRoute`. The `usersRoute` function will
get called with "/4873/profile.html" as a parameter. This means that `match`
will strip away the string it has matched from the input string before passing
it onto the route. `match` will also match routes in the order you have stated
them. This means that if you have the following route:

    myRoute = match
      [ "/user"   :-> userRoute
      , "/users"  :-> displayUserListing
      ] display404Page

There is no way for `displayUserListing` to ever be called. Say you pass in
"/users.html", then this will be matched by "/user" which will pass "s.html"
to `userRoute`. To solve this, you may wish to reverse the order of the routes
as follows:

    myRoute = match
      [ "/users"  :-> displayUserListing
      , "/user"   :-> userRoute
      ] display404Page

And now things will work as intended.

You may notice that in the first example, I use "/" as a route at the very top.
This is because `match` special cases "/" and the empty string due to their
prevalence.
values.type: List (Router.Router a) -> Router.Route a -> Router.Route a

values.name: matchPrefix
values.comment:
Takes a reference string and a string to match and returns the second string
stripped of the matched reference string. Used to implement `match`.

    matchPrefix "he" "hello" === Just "llo"

    matchPrefix "yo" "halo" === Nothing

docs.name: Array.MultiDim
docs.comment:
A class for multi-dimensional arrays, which stores the number of coordinates
at type-level.

Internally, the array is represented as a 1D array, so lookups
should be quite fast. However, we provide a safe, clean
interface for multi-dimensional lookups and updates.

To create an array, use a safe-list with the array dimensions:

    import List.SafeList exposing (cons, null)
    --Creates a 4x6x2 array of zeroes
    myArray =
      repeat (4 `cons` 6 `cons` 2 `cons` null ) 0

Accesses and updates use SafeList as well:

    import List.SafeList exposing (cons, null)
    updatedArray =
      case get (3 `cons` 1 `cons` 1 `cons` null ) myArray of
        Nothing -> myArray
        Just x ->
          set (3 `cons` 1 `cons` 1 `cons` null ) (2*x) myArray

If you ever give the wrong number of coordinates, you get a type error:

    --Won't compile
    updatedArray =
      case get (3 `cons` 1 `cons` 1 `cons` null ) myArray of
        Nothing -> myArray
        Just x ->
          set (3 `cons` 1 `cons` 1 `cons` null ) (2*x) myArray

We don't yet support any operations which change the size of the array,
such as push or append. For operations like `foldl` and `foldr`,
use the `toFlatArray` function, then the corresponding functions
on Array.Array.

@docs MultiDim, repeat, initialize

#Get array info
@docs inBounds, dims

#Access and update
@docs get, set

#Convting to flat List or Array
@docs toIndexedList, toFlatArray

#Mapping functions
@docs map, indexedMap

docs.name: List.SafeList
docs.comment:
This module provides a form of list which encode their length
in their type, using the TypeNats library. For example:

    someLength3 : List.SafeList Int (OnePlus (OnePlus (OnePlus (Zero))) )
    someLength3 = 2 `cons` 3 `cons` 4 `cons` null

List whose length doesn't match their type are forbidden.
For example:

    --Gives type mismatch
    badLength3 : SafeList Int (OnePlus (OnePlus  (Zero)) )
    badLength3 = 2 `cons` 3 `cons` 4 `cons` null

Because Elm doesn't have GADTs or DataKinds, it's impossible
to pattern match on SafeLists. Instead, we provide an "uncons"
function, which splits a list which we know to be non-empty
into its head and tail.

For example:

    sumFirstLast =
      let
        (h1, t1) = uncons someLength3
        (_, t2) = uncons t1
        (h3, t3) = uncons t2
        tailCheck : SafeList Int Zero
        tailCheck = t3
      in
        h1 + h3

This notation is awkward, so it's assumed this library
will be used on small lists only.


As well, many functions on List.List have been ported over,
though filter, foldl and foldr are notably absent, as they
do not preserve the length of the list.

Because Elm is not a higher-kinded language, it is not generally
possible to use this library when you don't know your list size in advance,
unless only generic functions like `map` are used.

# Our main type and pseudo-constructors
@docs SafeList, null, cons

# In lieu of pattern matching:
@docs uncons, toList, fromList

# The usual map functions
@docs map, map2, map3, map4, map5, unzip

# Length-preserving fold-like functions
@docs mapl, mapr, reverseMapr, scanl

# Functions for non-empty lists
@docs maximum, minimum, head, tail, last

# Utility functions
@docs  member, reverse, all, any

#Length-preserving sorting functions
@docs sort, sortBy, sortWith

docs.name: TypeNat
docs.comment:
Easy to remember names for type-level natural numbers.
These are intended only to be used as "phantom types:"
that is, there are no values of type `Zero` or `OnePlus a`.
Instead, they should be arguments to other type constructors.

Elm doesn't have DataKinds, so please don't do anything silly like
`OnePlus (OnePlus (OnePlus (List (Int, Int))))`
i.e. please only give another TypeNat as the argument to
OnePlus.

@docs Zero, OnePlus

types.comment:
A phantom type constructor to increment a TypeNat,
creating a larger TypeNat.

types.name: Zero
types.comment: A phantom type for 0, our base TypeNat.

values.comment:
Similar to the shape function, line allows you
to apply any LineStyle to a Line when converting it
to a form, giving you more fine grained control than
other similar functions.

values.comment: `polygon points` is a polygon bounded by `points`.

values.name: polyline
values.comment:
`polyline points` is a polyline with vertices
at `points`. (A polyline is a collection of connected
line segments. It can be thought of as drawing a 
"connect-the-dots" line through a list of points.)

values.comment:
Sets the position of a `Form`.

    -- 'circle' is now centered at (50,50)
    circle = position (50,50) circle

values.comment: Modifies the angle of a `Form`.

values.name: scale
values.comment: Modifies the scale of a `Form`.

values.name: segment
values.comment:
`segment (x1,y1) (x2,y2)` is a line segment with
endpoints at `(x1,y1)` and `(x2,y2)`.

values.name: shape
values.comment:
The `*Fill` and `*FillWithBorder` functions
allow you to add styling to your shapes and conver them
into forms, but sometimes those functions don't offer 
enough flexibility. What if you want a dashed border
instead of a solid one? Or how about a beveled join on
the border? For this you must turn to the shape function.
The `shape` function takes a `Shape` and *any* `ShapeStyle`
and converts them into a `Form`, giving you total control
over the styling of the shape.

values.name: size
values.comment: Sets the scale of a `Form`.

values.name: solid
values.comment:
`solid width color line` is a solid line of width `width` 
and color `color` whose path is described by `line`.

values.name: solidFill
values.comment: Fills a shape with a solid color.

values.comment:
Fills a shape with a solid color and borders it with a solid line.
Arguments specify fill color, border width and border color, respectively.
values.type: Color.Color -> Float -> Color.Color -> Graphics.Render.Shape -> Graphics.Render.Form msg

values.name: svg
values.comment:
Takes a `Form` and renders it to usable HTML, in this case
in the form of an SVG element. The first two arguments determine
the height and width of the SVG viewbox in pixels.
values.type: Float -> Float -> Graphics.Render.Form msg -> Html.Html msg

values.name: text
values.comment:
Similar to `shape` and `line`, the `text` function 
will take a string and any `TextStyle` and convert them
into a form. It is useful for when functions like `plain`
and `bold` don't offer enough flexibility and you need
more control over the styling of your text.

color.

docs.name: Json.Decode.Pipeline

values.name: custom
values.comment:
Run the given decoder and feed its result into the pipeline at this point.

Consider this example.

    import Json.Decode exposing (int, string, at, Decoder)
    import Json.Decode.Pipeline exposing (decode, required, custom)


    type alias User =
      { id : Int
      , name : String
      , email : String
      }


    userDecoder : Decoder User
    userDecoder =
      decode User
        |> required "id" int
        |> custom (at [ "profile", "name" ] string)
        |> required "email" string


    result : Result String User
    result =
      Json.Decode.decodeString
        userDecoder
        """
          {
            "id": 123,
            "email": "sam@example.com",
            "profile": {"name": "Sam"}
          }
        """
    -- Ok { id = 123, name = "Sam", email = "sam@example.com" }
values.type: Json.Decode.Decoder a -> Json.Decode.Decoder (a -> b) -> Json.Decode.Decoder b

values.name: decode
values.comment:
Begin a decoding pipeline. This is a synonym for [Json.Decode.succeed](http://package.elm-lang.org/packages/elm-lang/core/3.0.0/Json-Decode#succeed),
intended to make things read more clearly.

    import Json.Decode exposing (int, string, float, Decoder)
    import Json.Decode.Pipeline exposing (decode, required, optional)


    type alias User =
      { id : Int
      , email : String
      , name : String
      }


    userDecoder : Decoder User
    userDecoder =
      decode User
        |> required "id" int
        |> required "email" string
        |> optional "name" string ""

values.name: hardcoded
values.comment:
Rather than decoding anything, use a fixed value for the next step in the
pipeline. `harcoded` does not look at the JSON at all.

    import Json.Decode exposing (int, string, Decoder)
    import Json.Decode.Pipeline exposing (decode, required)


    type alias User =
      { id : Int
      , email : String
      , followers : Int
      }


    userDecoder : Decoder User
    userDecoder =
      decode User
        |> required "id" int
        |> required "email" string
        |> hardcoded 0


    result : Result String User
    result =
      Json.Decode.decodeString
        userDecoder
        """
          {"id": 123, "email": "sam@example.com"}
        """
    -- Ok { id = 123, email = "sam@example.com", followers = 0 }

values.name: nullable
values.comment:
Extract a value that might be `null`.

If the value is `null`, decodes to `Nothing`.
If the value is not `null`, runs the given decoder on it and...

* ...If that decoder succeeds, wraps its success value in a `Just`.
* ...If it fails, the entire decoding operation fails.


    import Json.Decode exposing (int, string, float, Decoder)
    import Json.Decode.Pipeline exposing (decode, required, optional)


    type alias User =
      { id : Int
      , email : String
      , name : Maybe String
      }


    userDecoder : Decoder User
    userDecoder =
      decode User
        |> required "id" int
        |> required "email" string
        |> required "name" (nullable string)

In the above example,

* If `name` is `null`, it will successfully decode to `Nothing`
* If `name` is `"Lee"` it will successfully decode to `Just "Lee"`
* If `name` is not present, the whole decoder will fail.

values.name: optional
values.comment:
Decode a field that may be missing or have a null value. If the field is
missing, then it decodes as the `fallback` value. If the field is present,
then `valDecoder` is used to decode its value. If `valDecoder` fails on a
`null` value, then the `fallback` is used as if the field were missing
entirely.

    import Json.Decode exposing (int, string, null, oneOf, Decoder)
    import Json.Decode.Pipeline exposing (decode, required, optional)


    type alias User =
      { id : Int
      , name : String
      , email : String
      }


    userDecoder : Decoder User
    userDecoder =
      decode User
        |> required "id" int
        |> optional "name" string "blah"
        |> required "email" string


    result : Result String User
    result =
      Json.Decode.decodeString
        userDecoder
        """
          {"id": 123, "email": "sam@example.com" }
        """
    -- Ok { id = 123, name = "blah", email = "sam@example.com" }

Because `valDecoder` is given an opportunity to decode `null` values before
resorting to the `fallback`, you can distinguish between missing and `null`
values if you need to:

    userDecoder2 =
        decode User
            |> required "id" int
            |> optional "name" (oneOf [ string, null "NULL" ]) "MISSING"
            |> required "email" string
values.type: String -> Json.Decode.Decoder a -> a -> Json.Decode.Decoder (a -> b) -> Json.Decode.Decoder b

values.name: optionalAt
values.comment: Decode an optional nested field.
values.type: List String -> Json.Decode.Decoder a -> a -> Json.Decode.Decoder (a -> b) -> Json.Decode.Decoder b

values.name: required
values.comment:
Decode a required field.

    import Json.Decode exposing (int, string, Decoder)
    import Json.Decode.Pipeline exposing (decode, required)


    type alias User =
      { id : Int
      , name : String
      , email : String
      }


    userDecoder : Decoder User
    userDecoder =
      decode User
        |> required "id" int
        |> required "name" string
        |> required "email" string


    result : Result String User
    result =
      Json.Decode.decodeString
        userDecoder
        """
          {"id": 123, "email": "sam@example.com", "name": "Sam"}
        """
    -- Ok { id = 123, name = "Sam", email = "sam@example.com" }
values.type: String -> Json.Decode.Decoder a -> Json.Decode.Decoder (a -> b) -> Json.Decode.Decoder b

values.name: requiredAt
values.comment: Decode a required nested field.
values.type: List String -> Json.Decode.Decoder a -> Json.Decode.Decoder (a -> b) -> Json.Decode.Decoder b

values.name: resolveResult
values.comment:
Convert a `Decoder (Result x a)` into a `Decoder a`. Useful when you want
to perform some custom processing just before completing the decoding operation.

    import Json.Decode exposing (int, string, float, Decoder)
    import Json.Decode.Pipeline exposing
      (decode, required, resolveResult)


    type alias User =
      { id : Int
      , email : String
      }


    userDecoder : Decoder User
    userDecoder =
      let
        -- asResult gets run *after* all the
        -- (|> required ...) steps are done.
        asResult : Int -> String -> Int -> Result String User
        asResult id email version =
          if version > 2 then
            Ok (User id email)
          else
            Err "This JSON is from a deprecated source. Please upgrade!"
      in
        decode asResult
          |> required "id" int
          |> required "email" string
          |> required "version" int -- version is part of asResult,
          |> resolveResult          -- but it is not a part of User


    result : Result String User
    result =
      Json.Decode.decodeString
        userDecoder
        """
          {"id": 123, "email": "sam@example.com", "version": 1}
        """
    -- Err "This JSON is from a deprecated source. Please upgrade!"

If there was a `<meta name="csrf-token">` tag in the page's `<head>` when

values.name: decoder
values.comment: Returns a decoder suitable for passing to `fromJson`.
values.type: Json.Decode.Decoder value -> Json.Decode.Decoder error -> Rails.ResponseDecoder error value

values.name: fromJson
values.comment:
Think `Http.fromJson`, but with additional effort to parse a non-20x response as JSON.

  * If the status code is in the 200 range, try to parse with the given `decoder.success`.
    * If parsing fails, return an `Http.UnexpectedPayload` wrapped in `HttpError`
  * If the status code is outside the 200 range, try to parse with the given `decoder.success`.
    * If parsing fails, return an `Http.BadResponse` wrapped in `HttpError`
values.type: Rails.ResponseDecoder error value -> Task.Task Http.RawError Http.Response -> Task.Task (Rails.Error error) value

values.name: get
values.comment:
Send a GET request to the given URL. You also specify how to decode the response.

    import Json.Decode (list, string)

    hats : Task (Error (List String)) (List String)
    hats =
      get (decoder (list string) (succeed ())) "http://example.com/hat-categories.json"
values.type: Rails.ResponseDecoder error value -> String -> Task.Task (Rails.Error error) value

values.name: post
values.comment:
Send a POST request to the given URL. You also specify how to decode the response.

  import Json.Decode (list, string)
  import Http

  hats : Task (Error (List String)) (List String)
  hats =
    post (decoder (list string) (succeed ())) "http://example.com/hat-categories.json" Http.empty
values.type: Rails.ResponseDecoder error value -> String -> Http.Body -> Task.Task (Rails.Error error) value

values.name: send
values.comment:
Utility for working with Rails. Wraps Http.send, passing an Authenticity Token along with the type of request. Suitable for use with `fromJson`:

    import Dict
    import Json.Decode (list, string)
    import Json.Encode as Encode
    import Http

    hats : HatStyle -> Task (Error (List String)) (List String)
    hats style =

      let
        payload =
          Encode.object
            [ ( "style", encodeHatStyle style ) ]

        body =
          Http.string (Encode.encode 0 payload)

        success =
          list string

        failure =
          Dict.fromList [ ("style", HatStyle) ]
            |> Rails.Decode.errors
      in
        send "POST" url body
          |> fromJson (decoder success failure)
values.type: String -> String -> Http.Body -> Task.Task Http.RawError Http.Response

docs.name: String.Extra

values.name: capitalize
values.comment:
Capitalize or uncapitalize the given string.

    capitalize True "foo"
    -- "Foo"

    capitalize False "BAR"
    -- "bAR"

values.name: isWhitespace
values.comment:
Returns True iff the given String is 1 or more whitespace characters,
and nothing else.

(Whitespace is defined as the regular expression `\s` matcher.)

    isWhitespace ""   == False
    isWhitespace " "  == True
    isWhitespace "  " == True
    isWhitespace " x" == False
    isWhitespace "x " == False

values.name: pluralize
values.comment:
Given a number, a singular string, and a plural string, returns the number
followed by a space, followed by either the singular string if the number was 1,
or the plural string otherwise.

    pluralize "elf" "elves" 2 == "2 elves"
    pluralize "elf" "elves" 1 == "1 elf"
    pluralize "elf" "elves" 0 == "0 elves"

values.name: toSentence
values.comment:
Converts a list of strings into a human formatted readable list


    toSentence [] ---> ""
    toSentence ["lions"] ---> "lions"
    toSentence ["lions", "tigers"] --> "lions and tigers"
    toSentence ["lions", "tigers", "bears"] --> "lions, tigers, and bears"

notes:
* It *DOES* include an oxford comma
* It *DOES NOT* include a period
* It *DOES NOT* include the phrase "...oh my!"

values.name: delay
values.comment: Delay a task by a given amount of time in milliseconds.
values.type: Time.Time -> Task.Task error value -> Task.Task error value

values.name: loop
values.comment:
Runs a task repeatedly every given milliseconds.

    loop 1000 myTask -- Runs `myTask` every second
values.type: Time.Time -> Task.Task error value -> Task.Task error ()

values.name: optional
values.comment:
Similar to `Task.sequence`.
The difference with `Task.sequence` is that it doesn't return an `error` if
any individual task fails. If an error is encountered, then this function will
march on and perform the next task ignoring the error.
values.type: List (Task.Task x value) -> Task.Task y (List value)

values.name: parallel
values.comment:
Analogous to `Task.sequence`.
Schedule a list of tasks to be performed in parallel as opposed to in series
as is the case with `Task.sequence`.

*Note that there is no guarantee that the tasks will be performed or complete
in the order you have stated. This is why you may use the returned `Process.Id`
for re-ordering or consider integrating a sorting mechanism within your program.*
values.type: List (Task.Task error value) -> Task.Task error (List Process.Id)

values.name: performFailproof
values.comment:
Command the runtime system to perform a task that is guaranteed to
not fail. The most important argument is the
[`Task`](http://package.elm-lang.org/packages/elm-lang/core/latest/Task#Task)
which describes what you want to happen. But you also need to provide
a function to tag the success outcome, so as to have a message to feed
back into your application. Unlike with the standard
[`perform`](http://package.elm-lang.org/packages/elm-lang/core/latest/Task#perform),
you need not provide a function to tag a failing outcome, because the
[`Never`](http://package.elm-lang.org/packages/elm-lang/core/latest/Basics#Never)
in the type `Task Never a` expresses that no possibly failing task is
allowed in that place anyway.

A typical use of the function is `Date.now |> performFailproof CurrentDate`.
values.type: (a -> msg) -> Task.Task Basics.Never a -> Platform.Cmd.Cmd msg

docs.name: Arborist.Framework
docs.comment:
Arborist is a test framework for asynchronous code.

It is intended for use mostly with Tasks. Tests are defined as assertions on
tasks, which are executed in parallel and reported on the command line.

# Declaring tests
@docs Test, Tests, Name, test

# Assertions
@docs assert, pass, fail, failWith

aliases.name: Name
aliases.comment: The name of a test.

aliases.name: Tests
aliases.comment: A list of `Test` cases.

types.name: Test
types.comment: A test case, usually constructed with the `test` function.

values.name: assert
values.comment:
`assert` runs a matcher against a value. All values are generally wrapped in tasks.

    let
      a = Task.succeed 7
      b = Task.succeed 3
      c = Task.map2 (+) a b
    in
      assert c (equals (Task.succeed 10))

This function is re-exported from `Arborist.Assertions` for your convenience.
values.type: Task.Task a b -> Arborist.Matchers.Matcher a b -> Arborist.Assertions.Assertion

values.name: fail
values.comment:
`fail` forces the test to fail.

This function is re-exported from `Arborist.Assertions` for your convenience.

values.name: failWith
values.comment:
`failWith` forces the test to fail with a reason.

This function is re-exported from `Arborist.Assertions` for your convenience.

values.name: pass
values.comment:
`pass` always passes.

This function is re-exported from `Arborist.Assertions` for your convenience.

values.name: test
values.comment:
Defines a test case.

    test "One plus one is most definitely two" (
      assert (Task.succeed (1 + 1)) (equals (Task.succeed 2))
    )

docs.name: Arborist.Matchers

aliases.name: Matcher
aliases.comment: A matcher is a function that accepts a value and asserts some property about it.

values.name: equals
values.comment:
Asserts that two values are equal.

    assert (Task.succeed "Hello!") (equals (Task.succeed "Hello!"))
values.type: Task.Task a b -> Arborist.Matchers.Matcher a b

values.name: fails
values.comment:
Asserts that another assertion fails.

    assert (assert (Task.succeed 1) (equals (Task.succeed 2))) fails

values.name: failsWith
values.comment:
Asserts that another assertion fails with specific failure messages.

    assert (assert (Task.succeed True) (equals (Task.succeed False))) failsWith [
      ("Expected", False),
      ("Actual", True)
    ]

values.name: isIntBetween
values.comment:
Asserts an integer is between two others, inclusive.

    assert (Task.succeed 24) (isIntBetween (Task.succeed 12) (Task.succeed 36))
values.type: Task.Task a Int -> Task.Task a Int -> Arborist.Matchers.Matcher a Int

values.name: not'
values.comment:
Negates another matcher.

    assert (Task.succeed 3) (not' (equals (Task.succeed 4)))
values.type: Arborist.Matchers.Matcher a b -> Arborist.Matchers.Matcher a b

values.name: onFailure
values.comment:
When constructing a matcher, adds failure messages.

If the matching operation results in an error, the error message is included in
the failure messages as the first item, with a name of "Error".

This function is often used with `sequenceMessages`.

    equals : Task a b -> Matcher a b
    equals expected actual =
      Task.map2 (==) expected actual |> onFailure (sequenceMessages [
        ("Expected", expected),
        ("Actual", actual)
      ])
values.type: Task.Task a Arborist.Assertions.FailureMessages -> Task.Task a Bool -> Arborist.Assertions.Assertion

values.name: sequenceMessages
values.comment:
Converts a list of failure messages which have value tasks into a task of failure messages.

    let
      a = Task.succeed 1
      b = Task.succeed 2
    in
      assert (sequenceMessages [("A", a), ("B", b)]) (equals (Task.succeed [("A", 1), ("B", 2)]))
values.type: List ( String, Task.Task a b ) -> Task.Task never Arborist.Assertions.FailureMessages

docs.name: Arborist.Assertions
docs.comment:
Provide a mechanism for asserting that a value (wrapped in a task)
successfully matches the behaviour outlined by the matcher.

# Assertions

@docs assert, pass, fail, failWith

# Types

The types provided are generally to be used when constructing your own matchers.

@docs Assertion, FailureMessage, FailureMessages

aliases.name: Assertion
aliases.comment: `Assertion` is a task representing either success, failure or error.

aliases.name: FailureMessage
aliases.comment: A `FailureMessage` consists of a name and a value to be displayed on failure.

aliases.name: FailureMessages
aliases.comment: `FailureMessages` is a list of `FailureMessage` values.

values.name: assert
values.comment:
`assert` runs a matcher against a value. All values are generally wrapped in tasks.

    let
      a = Task.succeed 7
      b = Task.succeed 3
      c = Task.map2 (+) a b
    in
      assert c (equals (Task.succeed 10))
values.type: Task.Task a b -> (Task.Task a b -> Arborist.Assertions.Assertion) -> Arborist.Assertions.Assertion

values.name: fail
values.comment: `fail` forces the test to fail.

values.name: failWith
values.comment: `failWith` forces the test to fail with a reason.

values.name: pass
values.comment: `pass` always passes.

values.comment:
Get the value associated with a key. If the key is not found, return
`Nothing`. This is useful when you are not sure if a key will be in the
dictionary.

    animals = fromList [ ("Tom", Cat), ("Jerry", Mouse) ]

    get "Tom"   animals == Just Cat
    get "Jerry" animals == Just Mouse
    get "Spike" animals == Nothing

values.comment:
Get all of the keys in a dictionary, sorted from lowest to highest.

    keys (fromList [(0,"Alice"),(1,"Bob")]) == [0,1]

values.name: map
values.comment: Apply a function to all values in a dictionary.
values.type: (comparable -> a -> b) -> CollectionsNg.Dict.Dict comparable a -> CollectionsNg.Dict.Dict comparable b

values.name: member
values.comment: Determine if a key is in a dictionary.

values.name: merge
values.comment:
The most general way of combining two dictionaries. You provide three
accumulators for when a given key appears:
  1. Only in the left dictionary.
  2. In both dictionaries.
  3. Only in the right dictionary.
You then traverse all the keys from lowest to highest, building up whatever
you want.
values.type: (comparable -> a -> result -> result) -> (comparable -> a -> b -> result -> result) -> (comparable -> b -> result -> result) -> CollectionsNg.Dict.Dict comparable a -> CollectionsNg.Dict.Dict comparable b -> result -> result

values.name: partition
values.comment:
Partition a dictionary according to a predicate. The first dictionary
contains all key-value pairs which satisfy the predicate, and the second
contains the rest.
values.type: (comparable -> v -> Bool) -> CollectionsNg.Dict.Dict comparable v -> ( CollectionsNg.Dict.Dict comparable v , CollectionsNg.Dict.Dict comparable v )

values.name: remove
values.comment:
Remove a key-value pair from a dictionary. If the key is not found,
no changes are made.
values.type: comparable -> CollectionsNg.Dict.Dict comparable v -> CollectionsNg.Dict.Dict comparable v

values.name: singleton
values.comment: Create a dictionary with one key-value pair.

values.name: size
values.comment: Determine the number of key-value pairs in the dictionary.

values.name: toList
values.comment: Convert a dictionary into an association list of key-value pairs, sorted by keys.
values.type: CollectionsNg.Dict.Dict comparable v -> List ( comparable, v )

values.name: union
values.comment:
Combine two dictionaries. If there is a collision, preference is given
to the first dictionary.
values.type: CollectionsNg.Dict.Dict comparable v -> CollectionsNg.Dict.Dict comparable v -> CollectionsNg.Dict.Dict comparable v

values.name: update
values.comment: Update the value of a dictionary for a specific key with a given function.
values.type: comparable -> (Maybe.Maybe v -> Maybe.Maybe v) -> CollectionsNg.Dict.Dict comparable v -> CollectionsNg.Dict.Dict comparable v

values.name: values
values.comment:
Get all of the values in a dictionary, in the order of their keys.

    values (fromList [(0,"Alice"),(1,"Bob")]) == ["Alice", "Bob"]

docs.name: CollectionsNg.Array

aliases.name: Array
aliases.comment:
Representation of fast immutable arrays. You can create arrays of integers
(`Array Int`) or strings (`Array String`) or any other type of value you can
dream up.
aliases.type: { length : Int, nodes : CollectionsNg.Hamt.Tree Int a }

values.name: append
values.comment:
Append two arrays to a new one.

    append (repeat 2 42) (repeat 3 81) == fromList [42,42,81,81,81]
values.type: CollectionsNg.Array.Array a -> CollectionsNg.Array.Array a -> CollectionsNg.Array.Array a

values.name: empty
values.comment:
Return an empty array.

    length empty == 0

values.name: filter
values.comment:
Keep only elements that satisfy the predicate:

    filter isEven (fromList [1..6]) == (fromList [2,4,6])

values.name: foldl
values.comment:
Reduce an array from the left. Read `foldl` as fold from the left.

    foldl (::) [] (fromList [1,2,3]) == [3,2,1]
values.type: (a -> b -> b) -> b -> CollectionsNg.Array.Array a -> b

values.name: foldr
values.comment:
Reduce an array from the right. Read `foldr` as fold from the right.

    foldr (+) 0 (repeat 3 5) == 15
values.type: (a -> b -> b) -> b -> CollectionsNg.Array.Array a -> b

values.name: fromList
values.comment: Create an array from a list.

values.name: get
values.comment:
Return Just the element at the index or Nothing if the index is out of range.

    get  0 (fromList [0,1,2]) == Just 0
    get  2 (fromList [0,1,2]) == Just 2
    get  5 (fromList [0,1,2]) == Nothing
    get -1 (fromList [0,1,2]) == Nothing

values.name: indexedMap
values.comment:
Apply a function on every element with its index as first argument.

    indexedMap (*) (fromList [5,5,5]) == fromList [0,5,10]
values.type: (Int -> a -> b) -> CollectionsNg.Array.Array a -> CollectionsNg.Array.Array b

values.name: initialize
values.comment:
Initialize an array. `initialize n f` creates an array of length `n` with
the element at index `i` initialized to the result of `(f i)`.

    initialize 4 identity    == fromList [0,1,2,3]
    initialize 4 (\n -> n*n) == fromList [0,1,4,9]
    initialize 4 (always 0)  == fromList [0,0,0,0]

values.name: isEmpty
values.comment:
Determine if an array is empty.

    isEmpty empty == True

values.name: length
values.comment:
Return the length of an array.

    length (fromList [1,2,3]) == 3

values.name: map
values.comment:
Apply a function on every element in an array.

    map sqrt (fromList [1,4,9]) == fromList [1,2,3]

values.name: push
values.comment:
Push an element to the end of an array.

    push 3 (fromList [1,2]) == fromList [1,2,3]

values.name: repeat
values.comment:
Creates an array with a given length, filled with a default element.

    repeat 5 0     == fromList [0,0,0,0,0]
    repeat 3 "cat" == fromList ["cat","cat","cat"]

Notice that `repeat 3 x` is the same as `initialize 3 (always x)`.

values.name: set
values.comment:
Set the element at a particular index. Returns an updated array.
If the index is out of range, the array is unaltered.

    set 1 7 (fromList [1,2,3]) == fromList [1,7,3]
values.type: Int -> a -> CollectionsNg.Array.Array a -> CollectionsNg.Array.Array a

values.name: slice
values.comment:
Get a sub-section of an array: `(slice start end array)`. The `start` is a
zero-based index where we will start our slice. The `end` is a zero-based index
that indicates the end of the slice. The slice extracts up to but not including
`end`.

    slice  0  3 (fromList [0,1,2,3,4]) == fromList [0,1,2]
    slice  1  4 (fromList [0,1,2,3,4]) == fromList [1,2,3]

Both the `start` and `end` indexes can be negative, indicating an offset from
the end of the array.

    slice  1 -1 (fromList [0,1,2,3,4]) == fromList [1,2,3]
    slice -2  5 (fromList [0,1,2,3,4]) == fromList [3,4]

This makes it pretty easy to `pop` the last element off of an array: `slice 0 -1 array`
values.type: Int -> Int -> CollectionsNg.Array.Array a -> CollectionsNg.Array.Array a

values.name: toIndexedList
values.comment:
Create an indexed list from an array. Each element of the array will be
paired with its index.

    toIndexedList (fromList ["cat","dog"]) == [(0,"cat"), (1,"dog")]

values.name: toList
values.comment:
Create a list of elements from an array.

    toList (fromList [3,5,8]) == [3,5,8]

values.name: add
values.comment:
Since cube coordinates come from 3d cartesian coordinates, I automatically get things like addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division. For example, you can have Hex(2, 0, -2) that represents two steps northeast, and add that to location Hex(3, -5, 2) the obvious way: Hex(2 + 3, 0 + -5, -2 + -2). With other coordinate systems like offset coordinates, you canâ€™t do that and get what you want. These operations are just what youâ€™d implement with 3d cartesian vectors, but I am using q, r, s names in this class instead of x, y, z

    IntCubeHex (2, 3, -5) +++ IntCubeHex (1, 2, -3) === IntCubeHex (3, 5, -8)

values.name: direction
values.comment: Direction relative to Hex polygon lines, we used shortcuts for the mix of North, East, South, West directions

values.name: distance
values.comment:
The distance between two hexes is the length of the line between them. 

    distance (IntCubeHex (2, 3, -5)) (FloatCubeHex (3.2, 4.3, -7.5)) == 2

values.name: eq
values.comment:
Compare two Hex definitions, support both axial and cubic coordinates.

Not a strict comparation, FloatCubeHex is converted to IntCubeHex.

    IntCubeHex (2, 3, -5) === IntCubeHex (2, 3, -5)
    AxialHex (2, 3) === AxialHex (2, 3)

values.name: floatFactory
values.comment:
Build Hex object from Float coordinates

    floatFactory (2.5, 3.5) === FloatCubeHex (2.5, 3.5, -6.0)

values.name: intFactory
values.comment:
Build Hex object from Int coordinates

    intFactory (2, 3) === IntCubeHex (2, 3, -5)

values.name: intQ
values.comment:
Get q coordinate for Hex as Int value, its generally not recommended to use on FloatCubeHex

    intQ IntCubeHex (2, 3, -5) == 2

values.name: intR
values.comment:
Get r coordinate for Hex as Int value, its generally not recommended to use on FloatCubeHex

    intR IntCubeHex (2, 3, -5) == 3

values.name: intS
values.comment:
Get s coordinate for Hex as Int value, its generally not recommended to use on FloatCubeHex

    intS IntCubeHex (2, 3, -5) == 3

values.name: length
values.comment:
Length of Hex.

    length (IntCubeHex (2, 3, -5)) == 5
    length (FloatCubeHex (2.2, 3.3, -5.5)) == 5

values.name: mul
values.comment:
Multiplication of Hexes, more info in `sum` description

    5 *** (IntCubeHex (2, 3, -5) === IntCubeHex (10, 15, -25))

values.name: neighbor
values.comment:
With distance, we defined two functions: length works on one argument and distance works with two. The same is true with neighbors. The direction function is with one argument and the neighbor function is with two.

    neighbor (IntCubeHex (2, 3, -5)) NW === IntCubeHex (2, 4, -6)

values.name: noteq
values.comment:
Compare two Hex definitions, if they are not equal, inversion of `eq` 

    IntCubeHex (2, 3, -5) !== IntCubeHex (1, 1, -2)
    AxialHex (2, 3) !== AxialHex (2, 1)

values.name: q
values.comment:
Get q coordinate for Hex as Float value 

    q IntCubeHex (2, 3, -5) == 2.0

values.name: r
values.comment:
Get r coordinate for Hex as Float value 

    r IntCubeHex (2, 3, -5) == 3.0

values.name: s
values.comment:
Get s coordinate for Hex as Float value 

    s IntCubeHex (2, 3, -5) == -5.0

values.name: sub
values.comment:
Subtraction of Hexes, more info in `sum` description

    (IntCubeHex (2, 3, -5) =-- IntCubeHex (1, 2, -3)) === IntCubeHex (1, 1, -2)

values.name: toFloatHex
values.comment:
Convert Hex to FloatCubeHex coordinate systems 

    toFloatHex (IntCubeHex (2, 3, -5)) === FloatCubeHex (2.0, 3.0, -5.0)

values.name: toIntHex
values.comment:
Convert Hex to IntCubeHex coordinate systems 

    toIntHex (FloatCubeHex (2.5, 3.5, -6.0)) === IntCubeHex (2, 4, -6)

values.name: cardView
values.comment:
A view function that will render the credit card.

This view will renders the credit card information such as the number, full name, expiration month/year, ccv, and the card logo.

This component also provide a card flipping animation for flipping back and forth between the front and back side of the card when displaying CCV number.
Some type of card has CCV printed on the front side of the card, in this case, the flipping animation will not be performed.

To use this view, just include this function as part of your view function. This will render the card as svg element.

Example:

    form []
        [ Html.App.map CreditCardMsg (CreditCard.Components.Card.cardView model.creditCardModel)
        , button [] [ text "Checkout "]
        ]

values.comment:
A view function that will render the input field for credit card CCV/CVC number.

To use this view, just include this function as part of your view function. The input field will only accept numeric input with maximum length of 4.

Example:

    form []

        , button [] [ text "Checkout "]
        ]

docs.name: Scroll
docs.comment:
This Library provides helper functions for handling events on scrolling.

# Types
@docs Update, Move, Direction

# Creating Scroll Handler
@docs handle

# On Event Handlers
Meant to be used with `Scroll.handle` to build up a list of possible events
for an application. All of the function signatures end in
`Move -> Maybe (Update m msg)` so they can be partially applied and used with
`Scroll.handle`.

## Basic
@docs onUp, onDown

## Complex
@docs onCrossUp, onCrossDown, onCrossOver, onInRange, onOverlap

# Helpers for Creating On Event Handlers
You can create your own as well which can be used with handle as long
they end in `Move -> Maybe (Update m msg)`. These are some functions that
can aid in the creation of them.

@docs direction, crossing

aliases.name: Move
aliases.comment:
Alias of (Float, Float) represents a move from a scroll position
to another scroll position 

    Move == (from, to)

aliases.name: Update
aliases.comment: Update m msg == m -> (m, Cmd msg)

types.name: Direction
types.comment:
Helps building your own triggers if direction is important.

    upAfterDown : Direction -> Event m msg -> Move ->  Maybe (Event m msg)
    upAfterDown lastDirection event move =
        if direction move != Up then
            Nothing 
        else if lastDirection == Scroll.Down  then
            Just event
        else
            Nothing

values.name: crossing
values.comment:
Notifies if a `Move` crosses a line. Nothing on no 
crossing and the direction on a crossing

values.name: direction
values.comment: A simple helper that returns the direction Up or Down of a Move

values.name: handle
values.comment:
Used in generating a function to trigger all possible events for a single
move. It returns in the standard pattern of `(Model, Effects Action)` the 
updates stack as well, so if many events trigger they update the model in order
they are in the list and the effects get thrown into `Effects.batch`.

    handleEvents : Move -> Model -> (Model, Effects a)
    handleEvents =
        Scroll.handle
            [ update TopBarDrop
              |> Scroll.onUp
            , update ToggleFixBar
              |> Scroll.onCrossOver 400
            ]

    update action model =
        case action of
            Transition move ->
                handleEvents move model
            TopBarDrop clockTime ->
                ...
            ToggleFixBar ->
                ...
values.type: List (Scroll.Move -> Maybe.Maybe (Scroll.Update m msg)) -> Scroll.Move -> m -> ( m, Platform.Cmd.Cmd msg )

values.name: onCrossDown
values.comment:
Triggers an update if move crosses the line downwards.

    update Action
    |> onCrossDown line
values.type: Float -> Scroll.Update m a -> Scroll.Move -> Maybe.Maybe (Scroll.Update m a)

values.name: onCrossOver
values.comment:
Triggers an update if move crosses the line in either direction.

values.name: onCrossUp
values.comment:
Triggers Update if move crosses the line upwards.

    update Action
    |> onCrossUp line
values.type: Float -> Scroll.Update m a -> Scroll.Move -> Maybe.Maybe (Scroll.Update m a)

values.name: onDown
values.comment:
Triggers an update on scrolling downwards

    update Action

values.type: Scroll.Update m a -> Scroll.Move -> Maybe.Maybe (Scroll.Update m a)

values.name: onInRange
values.comment:
Triggers an update if the new scroll position is in
the min max range

    update Action

values.type: Float -> Float -> Scroll.Update m a -> Scroll.Move -> Maybe.Maybe (Scroll.Update m a)

values.comment:

values.type: Float -> Float -> Scroll.Update m a -> Scroll.Move -> Maybe.Maybe (Scroll.Update m a)
